{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492748","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492748"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:43:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:43:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1147"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1147","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1147"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.33,0.17,0.41,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1147"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110363"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1147","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1147"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1147"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92636"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"33"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"194"},{"type":"tags","id":"272"},{"type":"tags","id":"318"},{"type":"tags","id":"650"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1372"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"2079"},{"type":"tags","id":"2245"},{"type":"tags","id":"2589"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"4607"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"7864"},{"type":"tags","id":"9600"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"843"},{"type":"contributions","id":"904"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14433"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17460"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41176"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41378"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42228"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44896"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110363","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110363"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 27-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department via ambulance following a high-speed motor vehicle accident. He is fully conscious, alert, oriented, and complaining of right-sided chest pain. Paramedics report that he has remained stable throughout transport and has been given pain relief with oral paracetamol and penthrox. Two large bore cannulas have been inserted but no fluid therapy administered. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His airway is patent, and a cervical spine collar has been applied. His Glasgow Coma Scale is 14, pulse rate is 125/min, blood pressure 90/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 19/min, SpO2 94% on room air and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. His trachea is midline, and he is tender over his right chest wall with pain limiting his inspiration. His peripheries are cool to touch and central capillary refill time 4 seconds. ECG is unremarkable. A CT scan of his chest reveals a haemopneumothorax (Images 1 - 2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most important next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intravenous fentanyl bolus","Bolus of 1 L normal saline","Needle thoracostomy","Large bore chest drain","One unit of O negative blood"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with signs of hypovolaemic shock following a high-speed motor vehicle accident, with CT evidence of a haemopneumothorax. The patient\u0027s tachycardia (125/min), hypotension (90/60 mmHg), cool peripheries, and prolonged capillary refill time indicate shock. In trauma patients, it is essential to identify and address the cause of shock rather than just treating the symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELarge bore chest drain\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step in management. The haemopneumothorax is the likely cause of the patient\u0027s haemodynamic instability, as blood accumulating in the pleural space represents ongoing internal haemorrhage and the pneumothorax can impair cardiac filling. Current trauma guidelines emphasise addressing the source of bleeding as the priority intervention. Inserting a chest drain will evacuate the accumulated blood and air, allowing lung re-expansion, improving ventilation, and most importantly, controlling the source of haemorrhage. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOne unit of O negative blood\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate as part of resuscitation, but not the most appropriate next step for this patient. Current resuscitation guidelines for haemorrhagic shock recommend blood products over crystalloids, as they replace what is being lost and avoid dilutional coagulopathy. However, without first controlling the source of bleeding with a chest drain, transfusion alone would be insufficient. The patient\u0027s systolic blood pressure of 90 mmHg is acceptable at this stage according to permissive hypotension strategies, which aim to maintain adequate organ perfusion without exacerbating bleeding until definitive haemorrhage control is achieved.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBolus of 1 L normal saline\u003C/strong\u003E is no longer considered optimal first-line management in haemorrhagic shock. While crystalloid boluses were historically used for initial resuscitation, current evidence suggests they may worsen outcomes through dilutional coagulopathy, hypothermia, and acidosis. Additionally, large volume crystalloid resuscitation without addressing the source of bleeding can increase hydrostatic pressure and potentially worsen haemorrhage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeedle thoracostomy\u003C/strong\u003E is indicated for tension pneumothorax, which is a clinical diagnosis characterised by respiratory distress, hypotension, tracheal deviation, and absent breath sounds. While this patient has a pneumothorax, there are no signs of tension physiology, making a formal chest drain the more appropriate intervention to address both the air and blood in the pleural space.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous fentanyl bolus\u003C/strong\u003E for pain management is not appropriate in a patient with haemodynamic instability. Opioids can cause vasodilation and further hypotension, potentially worsening the patient\u0027s shock state. Pain control is important but should be addressed after stabilising the patient\u0027s haemodynamics.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFollowing chest drain insertion, the next steps would include blood product resuscitation, continued monitoring, and further investigations to identify other potential injuries. This approach aligns with damage control resuscitation principles, which emphasise controlling haemorrhage, permissive hypotension, and balanced blood product administration. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["In trauma patients with haemopneumothorax, addressing the source of bleeding with chest drain insertion is the priority intervention.","Blood products are preferred over crystalloids for resuscitation in haemorrhagic shock."],"references":["Nickson C. Trauma! Major haemorrhage. Life in the Fast Lane (LITFL) [Internet]. 25 Sep 2020 [cited 2025 Jul 28]. Available from: https://litfl.com/major-haemorrhage-in-trauma/","Pumarejo Gomez L, Tran VH. Hemothorax. [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK538219/","Bauman ZM, Kulvatunyou N, Joseph B, et al. Randomized Clinical Trial of 14-French (14F) Pigtail Catheters versus 28\u201332F Chest Tubes in the Management of Patients with Traumatic Hemothorax and Hemopneumothorax. World J Surg 2021; 45:880\u2013t86"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92636"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1147"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"14585"},{"type":"media","id":"14586"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"14585","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/14585"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/85b681e7-0fb2-4d4b-919d-9835a56946d0.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/85b681e7-0fb2-4d4b-919d-9835a56946d0.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":538,"height":440}},{"type":"media","id":"14586","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/14586"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/dd86080c-0d3e-47db-98c2-514395c20c34.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/dd86080c-0d3e-47db-98c2-514395c20c34.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":542,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92636","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92636"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-30T15:26:15+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-30T15:26:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1147"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110363"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"33","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/33"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0",